- **PrespectiveAI** is a developer tool that provides translucent abstractions (visual, UI, programmatic - WASM or other, coupled with other tools, etc) for existing tools or development processes. It permits a seamless translation between the supposed obscure/opaque abstraction and actual implementation or original tool it builds on.
	- Renovating on the idea that programs are built with abstractions (on top of other programs), but in fact one can dig deeper and deeper to understand the software and unveil the abstraction. This tool provides the ability to seamlessly transition between high level implementaitons and equivalent low level implementation.
	- Steps to develop the vision: e.g. starting from providing translucent abstraction for common CLI tools. Using AI to understand the details and create automatically the abstraction relationship to low level implementation (i.e. the CLI commands themselves). Also AI will provide specific version support for the general abstraction approach.
		- Developers can use the abstraction as an overlay and then the abstraction program would permit to auto-type the equivalent command to the target OS window open. Just like the translation tool QTranslate or KeePassXC.
	- e.g. IDP allow for simplifying processes for DevOps through different abstractions [Kubernetes For Developers is the Next Big Thing](https://medium.com/@rphilogene/kubernetes-for-developers-is-the-next-big-thing-40d7077d141a); IDP tools recognize the need to make powerful technologies (like Kubernetes) more accessible and developer-friendly.
		- - "It’s not just about using the latest technologies; it’s about making them work for the people who use them. By bridging the gap between complex systems and developer-centric workflows, we can create a more efficient, productive, and enjoyable software development environment."
	- This also falls into the idea of visual programming with minimal bullk or actually visual-augmented text-based programming (i.e. providing transitive abstractions on existing tools not to hide the implementation but to empower and speedup the development.
		- e.g. an IDE with visual augmented extensions can detect a programming language syntax template and create overlay visuals on-top to make it easier to read and manipulate and detect while reviewing the code.
	- AI-Powered Development Tools that integrate visual elements and simplify complex systems. The AI tools provides multiple levels of visual overlay and design, which permit the programmer to match the low-level implementation with his expertise or even the comfort at which the current task requires (e.g. abstract functions into visual elements that can be toggled on demand to better navigate and draw relations in the system).

The root metascript can request actions from nested metascrpits which manage their own projects. This way an execution can mimic skaffold tool yet have all customization ability though internal wasm scripts and customized config files within each metascript. Question - how to pass arguments and call specific supported internal methods ? maybe must use an FS call interception (FUSE ?).
	- [LLM answer] "what is the equivalent in Linux to a file that hides many files internally like Powerpoint format that includes a complete folder inside?In Linux, the equivalent to a file that hides many files internally, similar to how PowerPoint (.pptx) packages multiple files and folders, is typically achieved using archive formats. These formats bundle multiple files and directories into a single file for easier storage, distribution, and sometimes compression."
	- [LLM answer] "Mounting Archive Files (Limited): Some tools and filesystems allow you to mount certain types of archives (like .iso images or some specialized archive formats) as virtual filesystems. This lets you browse the contents as if they were in a regular directory. However, directly editing files within a mounted standard archive (.tar.gz, .zip, .7z) and having those changes automatically written back to the archive is generally not supported."
- [LLM answer] "A potential solution for achieving PowerPoint-like in-place editing in Linux involves leveraging FUSE (Filesystem in Userspace) to create a custom filesystem that mounts a special archive file, presenting its internal contents as a regular directory. This custom filesystem would intercept file access and modification requests, updating the archive directly when changes are saved, thus providing a seemingly seamless editing experience for applications interacting with the mounted directory. However, this approach requires significant development effort to build the FUSE filesystem and define the custom archive format, and it's not a standard Linux feature."

- ### Names:
- **MMAI:** (Modular Multi-purpose AI) - Directly incorporates both "Modular" and "Multi-purpose."
- **MAIA:** (Modular Adaptable Intelligent Agent) - Sounds a bit like a name, which can be memorable.
- **VAM:** (Versatile AI Module) - Highlights versatility and the modular aspect.
- **OmniAI:** (Omni-purpose AI) - "Omni" implies doing many things.
- **PolyAI:** (Poly-functional AI) - "Poly" also means many.
- **MMM.ai** – Mega Modular Machine AI
